 for themselves, sacrificing for their families, and in their own way, being innovative and entrepreneurial in creating a vibrant local economy.","note":"Katherine Boo\r\nRandom House Trade, 2014","link_url":"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/081297932X/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"The Man Who Fed the World","blurb":"The subject of this book, Norm Borlaug, is one of my heroes — and Leon Hesser’s biography is a fascinating account of Borlaug’s life and accomplishments. This is a story of genius, self-sacrifice and determination. Borlaug was a remarkable scientist and humanitarian whose work in agriculture is rightfully credited with saving the lives of over a billion people. ","note":"Leon Hesser\r\nDurban House Press, 2010","link_url":"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0981848664/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"Energy Myths and Realities ","blurb":"Vaclav Smil is probably my favorite living author. If you care about energy issues, I recommend this volume, though its unvarnished look at the realities of energy use and infrastructure may be disconcerting to anyone who thinks solving our energy problems will be easy. Smil provides a rational framework for evaluating energy promises and important lessons to keep in mind if we’re to avert the looming climate crisis.","note":"Vaclav Smil\r\nAmerican Enterprise Institute for Public Policy Research, 2010","link_url":"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0844743283/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null}]},{"title":"Melinda Gates' recommended reading","description":"Those of us interested in development spend a lot of time thinking 